{"title": "A breakdown of President Trump\u2019s travel ban - The Boston Globe", "url": "https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2017/06/29/breakdown-president-trump-travel-ban/qxhVGR3PEtEfyxlOs54tsJ/story.html", "text": "Here\u2019s a closer look at the details of President Trump\u2019s travel ban:\n\nWhich countries are affected?\n\nThe travel ban affects new visa applicants from Syria, Sudan, Somalia, Libya, Iran, and Yemen, plus refugees from around the world.\n\nWhat\u2019s a \u2018close\u2019 family tie?\n\nAdvertisement\n\nVisa applicants from those countries must have a \u201cclose\u201d family or business tie to the United States, including a parent, spouse, child, adult son or daughter, son-in-law, daughter-in-law, or sibling already in the United States.\n\nGrandparents, grandchildren, aunts, uncles, nieces, nephews, cousins, brothers-in-law and sisters-in-law, fiancees, and other extended family members are not counted.\n\nWhat\u2019s a \u2018close\u2019 business tie?\n\nGet This Week in Politics in your inbox: A weekly recap of the top political stories from The Globe, sent right to your email. Sign Up Thank you for signing up! Sign up for more newsletters here\n\nThe State Department said a legitimate relationship must be \u2018\u2018formal, documented and formed in the ordinary course rather than for the purpose of evading\u2019\u2019 the ban. Journalists, students, workers or lecturers who have valid invitations or employment contracts in the US would be exempt from the ban. The exemption does not apply to those who seek a relationship with an American business or educational institution purely for the purpose of avoiding the rules. A hotel reservation or car rental contract would also not count.\n\nOther exceptions to the ban\n\nConsular officers may grant other exemptions if applicants have \u2018\u2018previously established significant contacts with the United States;\u2019\u2019 \u201csignificant business or professional obligations\u2019\u2019 in the US; if they are an infant, adopted child, or in need of urgent medical care; if they are traveling for business with a recognized international organization or the US government or if they are a legal resident of Canada who applies for a visa in Canada, according to the cable.", "source": "BostonGlobe.com", "publish_date": "2017-06-29", "type": "article"}